MLB Spread Analysis

William Xu

Introduction

In Major League Baseball, managers (coaches) are responsible for submitting lineups before every game. Ignoring teams that are purposely tanking, managers need to account for the opposing teams pitcher and batters. Stats such as ERA, Batting Average, Slugging, On Base Percentage, etc are considered while trying to construct a lineup. A possible way to construct such a lineup is to project a score or the spread of the game to see how each pitcher/batting line up matches up against another team. In this project, we explore data currated from Retrosheet in an attempt to map baseball offensive and defensive stats to a projected spread.

Data Set

The Retrosheet data set is a community driven database that keeps track of a wealth of detail about every game played since 1953. Each game contains information about every pitcher used, the scores after each innning, number of double plays, and even the umpires judging each game. For this project we’ll look just at data from last season 2017 which can be downloaded from http://www.retrosheet.org/gamelogs/index.html

Setup

Before we can start our analysis, we import a couple of R packages to assist in the process.

library(tidyverse)

Tidying Data

# select out important data from the main data frame
# mutate date to be a date type
tidied_df <- game_df %>%
    select(V1, V4, V7, V10, V11, V22, V23, V50, V51, V103, V105) %>%
    setNames(c("date", "away", "home", "away_score", "home_score", "away_ab", "away_hits", "home_ab", "home_hits", "away_pitcher", "home_pitcher")) %>%
    mutate(date = as.Date(as.character(date), "%Y%m%d")) %>%
    mutate(away_ba = away_hits/away_ab) %>%
    mutate(home_ba = home_hits/home_ab)

Data Exploration

Before creating our regression we look at how pitching and batting stats normalize throughout the season. We expect to see both these values normalize by the end of the regular season.

Pitching ERA

# merge home and away pitcher eras together and graph based on date

pitch_df <- tidied_df %>%
    select(date, away_score, away_pitcher) %>%
    setNames(c("date", "runs", "pitcher"))

temp_df <- tidied_df %>%
    select(date, home_score, home_pitcher) %>%
    setNames(c("date", "runs", "pitcher"))

pitch_df <- rbind(pitch_df, temp_df)

# get 5 pitchers and graph their dates vs runs
pitchers <- pitch_df %>%
    select(pitcher) %>%
    sample_n(5)

pitch_df %>%
    filter(pitcher %in% unlist(pitchers)) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x=date, y=runs, group=pitcher)) +
        geom_line(aes(color=pitcher)) +
        geom_point(aes(color=pitcher)) +
        labs(title="Runs vs Date per pitcher", x="Date", y="Runs Allowed")

Here we see there doesnt seem to be much normalization. Runs jump all over the place. A lot of this seems to deal with luck so we’ll look at pitchers averages through each game.

# Look at the cumulative average of pitchers through games
pitch_df %>%
    filter(pitcher %in% unlist(pitchers)) %>%
    mutate(avg_runs = ave(runs, pitcher, FUN = cummean)) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x=date, y=avg_runs, group=pitcher)) +
        geom_line(aes(color=pitcher)) +
        geom_point(aes(color=pitcher)) +
        labs(title = "pitcher era cumulative average vs date", x="date", y = "cumulative avg era")

Now we start to see a bit of a normalization towards a number. This means that the more times a pitcher appears, the more we confident we are in his actual earned run average. Now lets look at the cumulative standard deviation for these pitchers as the season goes on.

cumsd <- function(x) unlist(sapply(sapply(seq_along(x), head, x=x), sd))

pitch_df %>%
    filter(pitcher %in% unlist(pitchers)) %>%
    mutate(run_sd = ave(runs, pitcher, FUN = cumsd)) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x=date, y=run_sd, group=pitcher)) +
        geom_line(aes(color=pitcher)) +
        geom_point(aes(color=pitcher)) +
        labs(title = "pitcher era sd vs date", x= "date", y = "pitcher era sd")
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_path).
## Warning: Removed 5 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Our standard deviation shows that as more games are played, the standard deviation of runs allowed per pitcher lowers. This drop is not too large but we can see that with more data, we would see more decline. This means that central limit theroem holds for this data set.

Batting Average

Here we’ll do the same thing as for pitchers but look at a teams overall batting average instead.

# merge home and away batting stats together and graph based on date

bat_df <- tidied_df %>%
    select(date, away, away_ab, away_hits) %>%
    setNames(c("date", "team", "ab", "hit"))

temp_df <- tidied_df %>%
    select(date, home, home_ab, home_hits) %>%
    setNames(c("date", "team", "ab", "hit"))

bat_df <- rbind(bat_df, temp_df)

bat_df <- bat_df %>%
    mutate(batting_avg = hit/ab)

teams <- bat_df %>%
    select(team) %>%
    sample_n(3)

bat_df %>%
    filter(team %in% unlist(teams)) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x=date, y=batting_avg, group=team)) +
        geom_line(aes(color=team)) +
        geom_point(aes(color=team)) +
        labs(title="Batting Average vs Date per team", x="Date", y="Batting Average")

bat_df %>%
    filter(team %in% unlist(teams)) %>%
    mutate(avg_ba = ave(batting_avg, team, FUN = cummean)) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x=date, y=avg_ba, group=team)) +
        geom_line(aes(color=team)) +
        geom_point(aes(color=team)) +
        labs(title= "Date vs batting avg cumulative average", x = "date", y = "cumulative average batting average")

bat_df %>%
    filter(team %in% unlist(teams)) %>%
    mutate(sd = ave(batting_avg, team, FUN = cumsd)) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x=date, y=sd, group=team)) +
        geom_line(aes(color=team)) +
        geom_point(aes(color=team)) +
        labs(title="Date vs batting avg sd", x = "date", y = "batting average sd")       
## Warning: Removed 1 rows containing missing values (geom_path).
## Warning: Removed 3 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Looking at batting average we get a much better look at the normalization. Batting average starts all over the place and starts to approach a certain value. There are a couple jumps up and down on the graph but those seem to be associated with some other factor possibly a team having a very good day or very bad day relative to what they were supposed to do. The standard deviation starts large and then starts to center around a value. This shows the power of CLT and how the more data there is the more normal a dataset will look.

Regression

Now that we’ve looked at our data and know how data deviates around a central mean, we will use linear regression to see if there is a relationship between home and away pitching and batting average to calculate a potential outcome. The dependent variable in this experiment is the spread which is the away minus home score. The independent variables are the pitchers current era, the batters current batting average for home and away teams.

tidied_df <- tidied_df %>%
    mutate(away_pitch_era = ave(away_score, away_pitcher, FUN = cummean)) %>%
    mutate(home_pitch_era = ave(home_score, home_pitcher, FUN = cummean)) %>%
    mutate(away_ba_avg = ave(away_ba, away, FUN = cummean)) %>%
    mutate(home_ba_avg = ave(home_ba, home, FUN = cummean)) %>%
    mutate(spread = away_score - home_score)

model = lm(spread ~ away_pitch_era + home_pitch_era + away_ba_avg + home_ba_avg, data=tidied_df)

Regression Analysis

model %>%
    augment() %>%
    ggplot(aes(x=spread, y=.resid)) +
        geom_point() +
        labs(title="Actual vs Predicted", x = "Actual", y = "Projected")

model %>%
    tidy()
##             term   estimate  std.error   statistic      p.value
## 1    (Intercept)  0.1554885 1.28084599   0.1213952 9.033881e-01
## 2 away_pitch_era  1.0701958 0.04970053  21.5328842 2.975053e-94
## 3 home_pitch_era -0.9853332 0.04455114 -22.1169016 6.873373e-99
## 4    away_ba_avg -4.4745075 4.14358982  -1.0798626 2.803108e-01
## 5    home_ba_avg  1.7911239 3.93837589   0.4547874 6.493029e-01

The plot of spread to residuals shows a linear relationship between the two variables. This means there is some variable not included in the regression. Looking at the summary of the estimators, we see that only the pitcher eras are significant. This might be because the calculations on era early on were an exact linear transformation of the score. Later on this does not follow as well but given the data that we have we see this phenomeon.

Data Problems

The project was simplified given the data available. There were some major assumptions made to statistics that are not necessarily true and may have caused issues in this project. First ERA is calculated from a pitchers runs allowed divided by innings pitched multiplied by 9. We made a simplification here by just assuming the end score was the pitcher’s ERA. In most games this is a safe assumption but in many, pitchers will only play 6-7 innings and record a couple of earned runs. Relief pitchers then come in to close out games and we captured their ERA into our starting pitcher era which is not true. Another simplification we made was assuming pitching ERA normalized after just one season (2017 for this project). A solid starting pitcher is given roughly 32 starts in an entire season which is not necessary enough for our data analysis.

Conclusion

Projecting outcomes to MLB games is not an easy task. The best cappers for these predictions get about 53% correct given a cutoff line. We saw through our analysis that it is possible to project an outcome. Data trends towards a normal distribution which is what we want for a linear regression model. The more data that is used will give a better and more accurate representation of the model. Additionally adding more variables in to capture more advanced metrics could better capture the regression.
